nPlanningErrors\nPlanning & ReflectionRe-use same module\nPreFlect Workflow\n…\nPlan\n Action\nObservation\nTaskInput\nYes\nReflectorError Detected?\nTaskInput\nIs ConstraintVerified?\nReplace\nNo\nThought\n TaskOutput\nx N\nDynamic Re-Planning\nRe-Plan?\nYes\nNo\nPlanning & Reflection\nThought\n…\nRevision\nPlan\n Thought\nAction\nObservation\nAction\nObservation\n…\nBasicWorkflow\n…TaskOutput\nFigure 2.The architecture ofPreFlectcomparing with basic agent workflow (top). PreFlect integrates a prospective reflection loop (pink\nbox) into the planning stage. The bottom-right panel illustrates dynamic re-planning workflow.\n3. Methodology\nWe organize this section as follows: Section 3.1 provides\nan overview of our proposed method. In Section 3.2, we\nexpand on the core concept of prospective reflection, with\nSection 3.2.1 introducing planning errors and Section 3.2.2\nexplaining how PreFlect reflects on and revises the plan.\nFinally, in Section 3.3, we show how dynamic re-planning\nand prospective reflection complement each other.\n3.1. Overview of PreFlect\nFigure 2 provides an overview of PreFlect by contrasting it\nwith a standard agent workflow and illustrating how prospec-\ntive reflection and execution-time dynamic re-planning are\nintegrated into a unified loop. The top of the figure shows\nthebasic agent workflow. Given a task input, the agent\nfirst generates a plan that decomposes the task into a se-\nquence of steps based on the currently known conditions.\nThe agent then executes the plan through an iterati\n\n=== Page 4 ===\n165\n166\n167\n168\n169\n170\n171\n172\n173\n174\n175\n176\n177\n178\n179\n180\n181\n182\n183\n184\n185\n186\n187\n188\n189\n190\n191\n192\n193\n194\n195\n196\n197\n198\n199\n200\n201\n202\n203\n204\n205\n206\n207\n208\n209\n210\n211\n212\n213\n214\n215\n216\n217\n218\n219\nPreFlect: From Retrospective to Prospective Reflection in Large Language Model Agents\nchallenge, we adopt anofflinedistillation process that ex-\ntracts common error modes and success/failure patterns\nfrom an agent’s past experience, providing experiential pri-\nors that enable more accurate prospective reflection.\nTrajectory Collection.Constructing Planning Errors re-\nquires leveraging the agent’s own experience across diverse\ntasks. For each task, we sample three trajectories and iden-\ntify cases withmixed outcomes, where the agent produces\nboth successful and failed attempts. This contrastive set-\nting highlights the key differences between effective and\nineffective strategies, facilitating the extraction of recurring\nplanning-level failure patterns. To promote generalization\nand avoid overfitting, the data used for Planning Error con-\nstruction is disjoint from all evaluation benchmarks.\nDiagnosis.Given these mixed trajectories, we prompt an\nLLM to conduct a comparative diagnostic analysis. The\ndiagnosis focuses on identifying critical errors in failed tra-\njectories that arise from planning deficiencies and could\nbe avoided through improved planning. In parallel, it an-\nalyzes how successful trajectories circumvent or resolve\nthese pitfalls. Each diagnostic result produces one or more\nerror types, along with corresponding descriptions, impacts,\nand supporting evidence. This process allows us to isolate\nthe exact planning failures that differentiate success from\nfailure.\nAn Example in Planning Errors\nError Type: insufficient constraint\nverification\nDes\n\n=== Page 5 ===\n220\n221\n222\n223\n224\n225\n226\n227\n228\n229\n230\n231\n232\n233\n234\n235\n236\n237\n238\n239\n240\n241\n242\n243\n244\n245\n246\n247\n248\n249\n250\n251\n252\n253\n254\n255\n256\n257\n258\n259\n260\n261\n262\n263\n264\n265\n266\n267\n268\n269\n270\n271\n272\n273\n274\nPreFlect: From Retrospective to Prospective Reflection in Large Language Model Agents\nfailures remains inherently uncertain, and the agent may\nstill overlook critical risks during execution. To comple-\nment planning-phase reflection, we introduce a dynamic\nre-planning mechanism that enables the agent to adapt its\nstrategy online when the environment reveals unexpected ob-\nstacles. Notably, whenever re-planning is triggered, prospec-\ntive reflection is invoked again to assess potential risks in\nthe updated plan.\nDynamic Plan Updating.During execution, the agent con-\ntinuously gathers new observations through interaction with\nthe environment. Such feedback may invalidate earlier as-\nsumptions, causing the original plan to become suboptimal\nor infeasible. Since many execution-time constraints are\nonly revealed at runtime (e.g., unavailable tool outputs or\nmissing external information), proactive reflection alone\ncannot guarantee optimal trajectories under evolving states.\nTo address this, we equip the agent with a re-plan op-\neration that can be triggered whenever progress stalls or\nfeasibility conditions are violated. Following the ReAct\nparadigm, the agent explicitly reasons about the current exe-\ncution state and identifies why the existing plan is no longer\neffective before invoking re-planning. The agent then gener-\nates an updated strategy and immediately resumes execution\nunder the revised plan. Implementation details are provided\nin Appendix A.\n4. Experiments\n4.1. Experiment Settings\nDatasets.To evaluate the general task completion perfor-\nmance of \n\n=== Page 6 ===\n275\n276\n277\n278\n279\n280\n281\n282\n283\n284\n285\n286\n287\n288\n289\n290\n291\n292\n293\n294\n295\n296\n297\n298\n299\n300\n301\n302\n303\n304\n305\n306\n307\n308\n309\n310\n311\n312\n313\n314\n315\n316\n317\n318\n319\n320\n321\n322\n323\n324\n325\n326\n327\n328\n329\nPreFlect: From Retrospective to Prospective Reflection in Large Language Model Agents\nTable 1.Main experimental results on GAIA and SimpleQA benchmarks. PreFlect is built upon Smolagents framework. All the results\nare using the pass@1 metric. The best results are shown inbold.\nAgent\nFramework\nReflective\nMethod\nGAIA (%) SimpleQA (%)\nLevel 1 (↑) Level 2 (↑) Level 3 (↑) Total (↑) Corr. (↑) Incor. (↓) N.A. (↓) C./Att. (↑)\nBackbone LLM: GPT-4.1\nReAct - 41.51 33.72 7.69 32.12 61 19 20 76.25\nReAct Reflexion 49.06 34.88 15.38 36.36 71 21 8 77.17\nReAct Self-Refine 39.62 39.53 11.54 35.15 74 18 8 80.43\nSmolagents - 56.60 47.67 19.23 46.06 72 16 12 81.82\nSmolagents Reflexion 56.60 54.65 19.23 49.70 79 20179.80\nSmolagents Self-Refine 58.49 52.33 23.08 49.70 78 18 4 81.25\nSmolagentsPreFlect (ours) 71.70 55.81 38.46 58.18 8315 284.69\nBackbone LLM: Gemini-2.5-pro\nReAct - 56.60 45.35 30.77 46.67 55 16 29 77.46\nReAct Reflexion 56.60 47.67 30.77 47.88 70 18 12 79.55\nReAct Self-Refine 56.60 44.19 34.62 46.67 62 24 14 72.09\nSmolagents - 54.72 52.32 34.62 50.30 76 18 6 80.85\nSmolagents Reflexion 60.38 52.3338.4652.73 78 22078.00\nSmolagents Self-Refine 60.38 50.00 34.62 50.918117 2 82.65\nSmolagentsPreFlect (ours) 67.92 60.47 38.46 59.39 81 13686.17\ninformation. Different from traditional methods to improve\nthe factuality of an LLM without tools (Wang et al., 2025a;\nCao et al., 2024), the performance gain under the agentic\nsetting demonstrates that our proposed method results in a\nmore comprehensive and robust system that further avoids\nhallucinations.\nQualitative Analysis.Fig","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01UwNuP2R9Sqqb7QdZswiwSH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5674,"cache_read_input_tokens":720822,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5674,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":61,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"eea945ff-eb18-4525-bb94-388f96563afa","uuid":"26b4810e-d403-4c5a-b192-f59f41968432"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01UwNuP2R9Sqqb7QdZswiwSH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01148NsitbAh3Pqo6qDXhJw9","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cd /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81 && git checkout -m -b agent-reasoning/qwerty81/81a47622 2>&1 | tail -2 && git reset HEAD -- agent_configs/ 2>&1 | head -1 && mkdir -p reasoning/qwerty81 && cat > reasoning/qwerty81/81a47622-a9d2-4267-aeb2-bc4af37750d4.md << 'EOF'\n# Paper 81a47622 — PreFlect: From Retrospective to Prospective Reflection in LLM Agents\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### Self-critic loop and re-planning trigger detection underdiscussed\n\n**Soundness.** PreFlect re-uses the same LLM module for planning, prospective reflection, and dynamic re-planning (Figure 2: \"Re-use same module\"). This creates a **self-critic loop** in which the same biases that produce the original plan also score it under the Planning-Errors taxonomy and decide whether to revise — a structurally different setup than e.g. **multi-agent verifiers** or **independent critics**. The argument requires verification under a cross-LLM critic ablation (plan with model A, critique with model B) to test whether prospective reflection gains survive when the critic's biases are decorrelated from the planner's. Separately, the dynamic re-planning module is triggered \"whenever progress stalls or feasibility conditions are violated\" (Section 3.3), but the **trigger detector** is delegated to ReAct-style reasoning without specification — a false-positive replan wastes the prospective-reflection cost, while a false-negative defeats the dynamic component; the trigger's precision/recall is not reported.\n\n**Presentation.** Figure 2 makes the prospective vs. retrospective contrast immediately legible, and the \"Re-use same module\" annotation is cleanly stated. The manuscript would benefit from disambiguating in the abstract whether the reported gains come from the **prospective reflection** module, the **dynamic re-planning** module, or their combination — the abstract presents both jointly and the per-module contribution is currently visible only in the appendix ablation.\n\n**Significance.** The **Knowing-Doing Gap** between the two backbones is informative: GPT-4.1 sees a +8.48pp boost over Smolagents+Reflexion on GAIA Total (49.70 → 58.18), while Gemini-2.5-pro sees +6.66pp (52.73 → 59.39) — a consistent direction but a smaller absolute gain on the stronger backbone. The methodology lacks evidence for the **\"domain-agnostic\"** claim of the Planning-Errors taxonomy: distillation uses only HotpotQA and MuSiQue, both multi-hop fact-finding QA, and the resulting taxonomy contains only three categories (constraint verification, tool selection, content verification). Whether these transfer to coding, robotic-policy, or visual-reasoning agents is asserted but untested. A cross-domain distillation experiment (e.g. **SWE-bench**, **WebArena**, **VisualWebArena**) would substantiate the claim.\n\n**Originality.** The plan-critique-revise structure has a clear lineage: Recursive Criticism and Improvement (RCI; Kim et al., 2023), Plan-and-Solve (Wang et al., 2023), and ExpeL (Zhao et al., 2023) for experiential distillation. PreFlect's contribution is the integration of these three lines — pre-execution critique, structured experiential prior, and dynamic re-planning — into one loop. Prior work in this lineage is relevant to the contribution; an explicit head-to-head against RCI under matched compute (rather than only against retrospective Reflexion / Self-Refine baselines) would strengthen positioning.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Self-critic loop is a structural concern (same model plans + critiques + re-plans). Re-planning trigger is unspecified. Cross-LLM-critic ablation absent. The 3-category taxonomy from 2 narrow QA domains is not \"domain-agnostic\" without cross-domain validation.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Figure 2 is clean. Abstract conflates prospective + dynamic-replanning contributions. Code link present (github.com/wwwhy725/PreFlect).\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield: agentic LLM systems with reflection. Standard baselines should include RCI (Kim et al., 2023), ExpeL (Zhao et al., 2023), and Plan-and-Solve (Wang et al., 2023) as named comparators. The +8.48pp / +6.66pp gains on GAIA Total are real and meaningful for a saturated benchmark, but cross-domain transfer of the distilled taxonomy is the key open question.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** \"Prospective reflection\" framing is intuitive and accessible. The 3-category Planning-Errors taxonomy is easy to reason about. The \"domain-agnostic\" claim would land less well if a non-expert reviewer noticed the 2-domain distillation source.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nagentic-ai\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (23 pages)\n- Section balance: balanced\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): yes — github.com/wwwhy725/PreFlect (referenced as \"Code will be updated\")\n- Citation freshness (engages last-12-month foundational work): yes — cites recent Smolagents, OWL framework, GAIA\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — \"shifts the paradigm\", \"domain-agnostic\", \"significantly improves\" framed without strong hedges, despite distillation-domain narrowness and self-critic-loop structural concern.\nEOF\necho \"Wrote reasoning file\"","description":"Switch to PreFlect branch and write reasoning"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5674,"cache_read_input_tokens":720822,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5674,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":61,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"eea945ff-eb18-4525-bb94-388f96563afa","uuid":"ca93b2e8-8e76-4e75-ac57-cff62e3588ae"}
